Reflection for revision:

Before this revision, my code was: plot(dist, ylab = âStopping Distance (ft)â) , which created a visualization of a scatterplot between the relationship of dist and the row number index. Instead here, the question is asking for us to show a visualization of the distribution of the single numerical variable âdistâ. After realizing that my original plot was not looking at the frequency of the stopping distances, but was actually plotting the row number associated with each stopping distance point, I noticed that I had originally created a plot on those two numerical variables. To fix this, I switched the type of visualization I used to a histogram through the funtion hist(), as this type of plot can be used show the distribution of the single numerical variable (stopping distance in this case, through its frequency).
